"The paradigms in pharmacognosy represent the evolving frameworks, models, and methodological approaches that guide research, education, and application in the field. Pharmacognosy has transitioned from a primarily descriptive botanical science to a multidisciplinary, technology-driven discipline. These paradigms are not mutually exclusive but reflect historical development and contemporary integration. 

jaimonline.org +1

1. Classical/Traditional Paradigm (Descriptive/Botanical Pharmacognosy)
Core Focus: Authentication, identification, and quality control of crude drugs (plants, animals, minerals) using macroscopic (organoleptic), microscopic (histological), and physicochemical methods. Emphasis on materia medica, taxonomy, and standardization of raw materials.
Strengths: Foundational for pharmacopoeial standards, herbal product quality assurance, and combating adulteration/substitution.
Context: Dominant in the 19th–early 20th century; remains essential for regulatory and industrial applications (e.g., dietary supplements). 

en.wikipedia.org

Limitations: Limited to morphology/chemistry without deep mechanistic insights or bioactivity correlation.

2. Phytochemical and Bioassay-Guided Paradigm (Chemical/Isolation-Focused)
Core Focus: Extraction, isolation, structure elucidation (via chromatography, spectroscopy: HPLC, NMR, MS), and bioactivity screening of secondary metabolites (alkaloids, terpenoids, flavonoids, etc.).
Approach: Bioassay-guided fractionation to link compounds to pharmacological effects. Dereplication to avoid known compounds.
Contributions: Led to many blockbuster drugs (e.g., paclitaxel, artemisinin, morphine derivatives). Still central to natural products chemistry. 

jbph.org

Evolution: Integrated with high-throughput screening but challenged by rediscovery rates and supply issues.

3. Ethnopharmacological and Traditional Knowledge-Inspired Paradigm
Core Focus: Validation of indigenous/traditional uses (Ayurveda, TCM, African, Amazonian, etc.) through scientific methods. Reverse pharmacognosy (starting from clinical/traditional effects to molecules).
Key Elements: Benefit-sharing (Nagoya Protocol), cultural preservation, and synergy studies of multi-component herbal formulations.
Paradigm Shift: From viewing tradition as anecdotal to a hypothesis-generating resource for drug discovery and evidence-based integration. 

pubs.acs.org +1

4. Molecular, Genomic, and Metabolomic Paradigm (Omics-Driven)
Core Focus: DNA barcoding/genomics for authentication and biosynthetic gene cluster mining; metabolomics for profiling complex mixtures; proteomics and transcriptomics for mechanisms.
Tools: Genome mining, molecular networking (e.g., GNPS), CRISPR-enabled pathway engineering.
Emerging Subfields: Molecular pharmacognosy, genomic pharmacognosy, metabolomic pharmacognosy. These enable precision authentication, sustainable production (e.g., via synthetic biology), and systems-level understanding. 

sciencedirect.com +1

5. Systems/Network Pharmacology and Translational Paradigm
Core Focus: Multi-target, holistic effects of natural product mixtures rather than single compounds. Network analysis of interactions with biological systems.
Approach: Integration with bioinformatics, AI/machine learning for virtual screening, predictive modeling, and clinical translation. Emphasis on standardization, bioavailability, and clinical pharmacognosy.
Relevance: Addresses complexity of herbal medicines and chronic diseases; supports "clinical pharmacognosy" and regulatory pathways for botanicals. 

healthcare-bulletin.co.uk

6. Emerging and Integrative Paradigms
Microbiome-Mediated Pharmacognosy: Role of endophytes, gut microbiota in metabolite production and activity. 

researchgate.net

Sustainable/Biotechnological Paradigm: Plant cell/tissue culture, metabolic engineering, marine/extremophile sources, and green chemistry to address biodiversity loss.
Digital/Contextualized Pharmacognosy: AI for data integration, big data from omics, and contextual (ecological, evolutionary) understanding beyond isolated extracts. 

sciencedirect.com

One Health/Interdisciplinary: Linking pharmacognosy with ecology, conservation, and global health.

Overarching Shifts and Future Outlook
Pharmacognosy has undergone a renaissance in the 21st century, moving from reductionist, single-target models to integrative, systems-oriented, and sustainable frameworks. Key drivers include technological advances (omics, AI), global demand for evidence-based natural therapies, antimicrobial resistance, and sustainability imperatives. 

